  "prompt": "What steps should I follow to find the mechanical advantage of a simple machine?",
  "response": "To find the **mechanical advantage (MA)** of a simple machine, follow these steps:\n\n### 1. **Identify the Type of Simple Machine**\n   Determine which type of simple machine you are analyzing. Common examples include:\n   - Levers\n   - Pulleys\n   - Inclined planes\n   - Wedges\n   - Screws\n   - Wheel and axle\n\n### 2. **Understand the Formula for Mechanical Advantage**\n   The mechanical advantage is a measure of how much a machine multiplies the input force. The general formula is:\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Mechanical Advantage (MA)} = \\frac{\\text{Output Force (Load)}}{\\text{Input Force (Effort)}}\n   \\]\n\n   Alternatively, for machines that involve distance or movement:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Mechanical Advantage (MA)} = \\frac{\\text{Input Distance}}{\\text{Output Distance}}\n   \\]\n\n### 3. **Determine the Input and Output Forces (or Distances)**\n   - **Output Force (Load):** The force exerted by the machine to do work (e.g., lifting a weight).\n   - **Input Force (Effort):** The force you apply to the machine to operate it.\n   - **Input Distance:** The distance over which the effort is applied.\n   - **Output Distance:** The distance the load is moved.\n\n### 4. **Apply the Formula**\n   Plug the values of the input and output forces (or distances) into the formula to calculate the mechanical advantage.\n\n---\n\n### Example Calculations:\n#### **Lever (First Class):**\n   - **Input Force (Effort):** 20 N\n   - **Output Force (Load):** 100 N\n   - \\[\n   \\text{MA} = \\frac{\\text{Load}}{\\text{Effort}} = \\frac{100\\,N}{20\\,N} = 5\n   \\]\n\n#### **Inclined Plane:**\n   - **Input Distance:** 6 m (length of the plane)\n   - **Output Distance:** 2 m (height of the plane)\n   - \\[\n   \\text{MA} = \\frac{\\text{Input Distance}}{\\text{Output Distance}} = \\frac{6\\,m}{2\\,m} = 3\n   \\]\n\n### 5. **Interpret the Result**\n   A mechanical advantage greater than 1 means the machine multiplies the input force, making the work easier. If it is less than 1, the machine increases distance or speed but reduces force.\n\nBy following these steps, you can calculate the mechanical advantage of any simple machine!",
